Unified Frameworks for Recursive Architecture and Structural Stability: A Technical Briefing

Executive Summary

This briefing synthesizes recent advancements in deep learning architectures, focusing on the transition from static, human-designed models to autonomous, self-optimizing recursive systems. The core findings identify Dynamical Isometry and Recursive Distinction Depth (RDD) as the critical thresholds for achieving stable, meta-cognitive AI.

Key innovations include the JPmHC framework, which utilizes orthogonal hyper-connections to prevent spectral collapse in deep networks; the Share method, which enables strict continual learning through a universal foundational subspace; and the HALIRA framework, which formalizes logical paradoxes as structural filtration layers. Together, these frameworks provide a blueprint for "Auto Self-Bootstrapping"—the process by which an AI system autonomously identifies, evaluates, and navigates its own design space to achieve deep research capabilities and terminal structural stability.


