1. Preserving Dynamical Isometry: The JPmHC Framework

Training deep architectures requires that the singular values of the input-output Jacobian remain concentrated near 1, a property known as Dynamical Isometry. Standard residual connections often bias mappings toward the identity, limiting expressivity, while unconstrained "Hyper-Connections" (HC) lead to signal gains and instability.

1.1 Spectral Diagnosis and Failure Modes

Analysis of doubly stochastic (bistochastic) mixers—commonly used in manifold-constrained HC—reveals two primary failure modes that break dynamical isometry:

* Eigenvalue Contraction: Deep composition drives all eigenvalues (except the Perron eigenvalue) toward zero.
* Eigenspace Misalignment: Non-commuting layers scramble directions, accelerating the collapse of the singular-value distribution.

1.2 The Orthogonal Solution (JPmHC-Cayley)

To eliminate these failures, JPmHC proposes constraining the residual mixer to the Orthogonal Group O(n) using the Cayley Transform.

* Property: Orthogonal matrices preserve norms and prevent misalignment through group closure under composition.
* Implementation: Skew-symmetric matrices are mapped to orthogonal ones via iterative Cayley projections (s=2 iterations), which is computationally more efficient than the Sinkhorn-Knopp iterations used for bistochastic constraints.
* Empirical Gains: In ARC-AGI benchmarks, the Cayley variant achieved a 1.41× improvement in exact-match accuracy and 2.25× fewer FLOPs per module compared to Sinkhorn-based methods.

1.3 Operator-Valued Free Probability

JPmHC employs an operator-valued numerical pipeline to predict Jacobian spectra. By leveraging the Kronecker structure (A_n \otimes I_p), the spectral problem collapses from the network width (N=np) to the twist dimension (n), reducing computational complexity by factors as high as 10^5.


