3. Parameter-Efficient Continual Learning: The Share Method

A critical hurdle in recursive architectures is the high cost of retraining and "catastrophic forgetting." The Share method addresses this by leveraging the Universal Weight Subspace Hypothesis.

3.1 The Shared Foundational Subspace

Instead of maintaining separate LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation) adapters for every new task, Share identifies a common low-rank subspace across tasks.

* Mechanism: Principal basis vectors (\alpha, \beta) are extracted via SVD from initial adapters and frozen. Only task-specific coefficients (\epsilon) are learned for new data.
* Knowledge Integration: When new tasks arrive, Share performs a "Continual Adaptation" by adding temporary factors, followed by a "Merging & Fine-tuning" phase that analytically reprojects older knowledge to minimize interference.

3.2 Efficiency Metrics

Share demonstrates significant advantages over traditional LoRA methods:

* Parameter Reduction: Up to 100× reduction in trainable parameters.
* Memory Savings: Up to 281× savings, enabling a single model to replace hundreds of task-specific adapters.
* Forward/Backward Transfer: By refining the shared subspace, later tasks can improve performance on earlier tasks (backward transfer), a phenomenon rarely seen in standard continual learning.


